  15. (**************************************************************************)

  17. (** Target processor-native integers.

  19.    This module provides operations on the type of
  20.    signed 32-bit integers (on 32-bit target platforms) or
  21.    signed 64-bit integers (on 64-bit target platforms).
  22.    This integer type has exactly the same width as that of a
  23.    pointer type in the C compiler.  All arithmetic operations over
  24.    are taken modulo 2{^32} or 2{^64} depending
  25.    on the word size of the target architecture.

  27.   {b Warning:} this module is unstable and part of
  28.   {{!Compiler_libs}compiler-libs}.

  30. *)

  32. ‌type t
  33. (** The type of target integers. *)

  36. (** The target integer 0.*)

  42. (** The target integer -1.*)

  56. ‌val div : t -> t -> t
  57. (** Integer division.  Raise [Division_by_zero] if the second
  58.    argument is zero.  This division rounds the real quotient of
  59.    its arguments towards zero, as specified for {!Stdlib.(/)}. *)

  61. ‌val unsigned_div : t -> t -> t
  62. (** Same as {!div}, except that arguments and result are interpreted as {e
  63.     unsigned} integers. *)

  65. ‌val rem : t -> t -> t
  66. (** Integer remainder.  If [y] is not zero, the result
  67.    of [Targetint.rem x y] satisfies the following properties:
  68.    [Targetint.zero <= Nativeint.rem x y < Targetint.abs y] and
  69.    [x = Targetint.add (Targetint.mul (Targetint.div x y) y)
  70.                       (Targetint.rem x y)].
  71.    If [y = 0], [Targetint.rem x y] raises [Division_by_zero]. *)

  73. ‌val unsigned_rem : t -> t -> t
  74. (** Same as {!rem}, except that arguments and result are interpreted as {e
  75.     unsigned} integers. *)

  77. ‌val succ : t -> t
  78. (** Successor.
  79.    [Targetint.succ x] is [Targetint.add x Targetint.one]. *)

  81. ‌val pred : t -> t
  82. (** Predecessor.
  83.    [Targetint.pred x] is [Targetint.sub x Targetint.one]. *)

  85. ‌val abs : t -> t
  86. (** [abs x] is the absolute value of [x]. On [min_int] this
  87.    is [min_int] itself and thus remains negative. *)

  89. ‌val size : int
  90. (** The size in bits of a target native integer. *)

  92. ‌val max_int : t
  93. (** The greatest representable target integer,
  94.     either 2{^31} - 1 on a 32-bit platform,
  95.     or 2{^63} - 1 on a 64-bit platform. *)

  97. ‌val min_int : t
  98. (** The smallest representable target integer,
  99.    either -2{^31} on a 32-bit platform,
  100.    or -2{^63} on a 64-bit platform. *)

  102. ‌val logand : t -> t -> t
  103. (** Bitwise logical and. *)

  112. (** Bitwise logical negation. *)

  114. ‌val shift_left : t -> int -> t
  115. (** [Targetint.shift_left x y] shifts [x] to the left by [y] bits.
  116.     The result is unspecified if [y < 0] or [y >= bitsize],
  117.     where [bitsize] is [32] on a 32-bit platform and
  118.     [64] on a 64-bit platform. *)

  120. ‌val shift_right : t -> int -> t
  121. (** [Targetint.shift_right x y] shifts [x] to the right by [y] bits.
  122.     This is an arithmetic shift: the sign bit of [x] is replicated
  123.     and inserted in the vacated bits.
  124.     The result is unspecified if [y < 0] or [y >= bitsize]. *)

  126. ‌val shift_right_logical : t -> int -> t
  127. (** [Targetint.shift_right_logical x y] shifts [x] to the right
  128.     by [y] bits.
  129.     This is a logical shift: zeroes are inserted in the vacated bits
  130.     regardless of the sign of [x].
  131.     The result is unspecified if [y < 0] or [y >= bitsize]. *)

  133. ‌val of_int : int -> t
  134. (** Convert the given integer (type [int]) to a target integer
  135.     (type [t]), module the target word size. *)

  137. ‌val of_int_exn : int -> t
  138. (** Convert the given integer (type [int]) to a target integer
  139.     (type [t]).  Raises a fatal error if the conversion is not exact. *)

  141. ‌val to_int : t -> int
  142. (** Convert the given target integer (type [t]) to an
  143.     integer (type [int]).  The high-order bit is lost during
  144.     the conversion. *)

  146. ‌val of_float : float -> t
  147. (** Convert the given floating-point number to a target integer,
  148.    discarding the fractional part (truncate towards 0).
  149.    The result of the conversion is undefined if, after truncation,
  150.    the number is outside the range
  151.    \[{!Targetint.min_int}, {!Targetint.max_int}\]. *)

  153. ‌val to_float : t -> float
  154. (** Convert the given target integer to a floating-point number. *)

  156. ‌val of_int32 : int32 -> t
  157. (** Convert the given 32-bit integer (type [int32])
  158.     to a target integer. *)

  160. ‌val to_int32 : t -> int32
  161. (** Convert the given target integer to a
  162.     32-bit integer (type [int32]).  On 64-bit platforms,
  163.     the 64-bit native integer is taken modulo 2{^32},
  164.     i.e. the top 32 bits are lost.  On 32-bit platforms,
  165.     the conversion is exact. *)

  167. ‌val of_int64 : int64 -> t
  168. (** Convert the given 64-bit integer (type [int64])
  169.     to a target integer. *)

  171. ‌val to_int64 : t -> int64
  172. (** Convert the given target integer to a
  173.     64-bit integer (type [int64]). *)

  175. ‌val of_string : string -> t
  176. (** Convert the given string to a target integer.
  177.     The string is read in decimal (by default) or in hexadecimal,
  178.     octal or binary if the string begins with [0x], [0o] or [0b]
  179.     respectively.
  180.     Raise [Failure "int_of_string"] if the given string is not
  181.     a valid representation of an integer, or if the integer represented
  182.     exceeds the range of integers representable in type [nativeint]. *)

  184. ‌val to_string : t -> string
  185. (** Return the string representation of its argument, in decimal. *)

  187. ‌val compare: t -> t -> int
  188. (** The comparison function for target integers, with the same specification as
  189.     {!Stdlib.compare}.  Along with the type [t], this function [compare]
  190.     allows the module [Targetint] to be passed as argument to the functors
  191.     {!Set.Make} and {!Map.Make}. *)

  193. ‌val unsigned_compare: t -> t -> int
  194. (** Same as {!compare}, except that arguments are interpreted as {e unsigned}
  195.     integers. *)

  197. ‌val equal: t -> t -> bool
  198. (** The equal function for target ints. *)

  204. ‌val repr : t -> repr
  205. (** The concrete representation of a native integer. *)

  208. (** Print a target integer to a formatter. *)
